In the 1850s the Mueller family acquired the west half of Nicholls County. They farmed and ranched until they were forced to evacuate under General Order Number 11. After the Civil War they rebuilt their burned-out ranch and resumed operations until the 1870s: better land was to be found in Minnesota: the land here was not very productive for farming or ranching. While Snake Woods itself, both in the upper grounds and down in the ravine seemed to flourish, the land around it was parched for miles, almost soilless even past the area that would become the POW camp.  East of Snake Woods the ravine emptied out onto flat land.  A spring fed very shallow, algae covered rocks where dragonflies danced and mosquitoes hunted, but the water was too shallow for anything but insects.  There were a few pools but they were also shallow and far between and reeked. Westward from Snake Woods there also were no trees for miles and the soil slowly returned to normal prairie.\par
\par
To the eye the land looked completely flat, somehow barren wasteland, but there were rolling prairie hills with cottonwoods, black locusts and Osage oranges clinging to the the creekbeds. But the creeks were in unusually incised channels and there was not much width to them.\par
\par
From late 1942 to 1946 the deserted Mueller Ranch housed a POW camp for Italian officers on a leveled-out area over a mile long and over half a mile wide that went down into bedrock for much of its length. The POWs were set to finding the treasure, and anywhere there was soil was a place they dug up.  The soil was left in mounds or blew away.  In 1944 it was repurposed for German enlisted personnel and officers deemed dangerous:  the new orientation was more disciplinary: among the inmates were hard-core Nazis and soldiers who had attempted to escape, assaulted guards or fellow inmates. The Italian prisoners would be seen cleaning streets in Nicholls and they were trucked to work farms, but the camp underwent a sea-change, and even the guards were changed.  The later prisoners were taken directly to the camp and confined, and the guards never mingled in town. Unprovable, ugly rumors came from the camp, but no one in town knew the truth. All prisoners were repatriated in 1946, directly moved from the camp to the train station still under guard, and the camp was mostly razed. They repatriated the dead as well, and the graves were filled with gravel.  \par
\par
The camp quarried high quality limestone on its western edge, first to produce stone, later more as a disciplinary incentive. The Italians built a beautiful stone chapel as well as a few small walls. During the German internment the rock was mainly used as gravel to widen the field of fire around the camp. The army razed most of the camp after the war, pushing the buildings into large piles and burning them.  Broken glass and metal were also in the debris.  The quarry was also filled with debris, which was then set on fire. The army handed the property over to the Benedictines after the war as the Muellers could not then be found, according to some, or refused to accept the land back, according to others. Somehow it became Benedictine property.   The monks converted the few remaining buildings into a Retreat Center, including the stone chapel,  but maintenance issues and better facilities elsewhere caused them to close it. In 1967 the order offered it to the Boy Scouts and again to the military.  They had hoped the army would keep it as a bombing range or other purposes that would force the army to keep it forever. Neither the Scouts nor the military was interested.  The order kept the land until their lawyers found a clause that made the  land revert to the Muellers, who disputed it but were unwilling to take it to court. As church land, there had been no property taxes, but as private property there would be some.  The Muellers threatened to not pay the taxes and then the county would own it, but the county did not want it.  So the taxes were set to zero and the Muellers kept it.\par
 \par
\lang9 After the Benedictines left the gate vanished. The quarry became a dumping ground for old appliances, refrigerators, cars, garbage and trash of all kinds on top of what had been pushed into it after the war. But all the copper and electrical wire, plumbing pipes and anything of value was stripped from the buildings, which, aside from the stone chapel and a few small ornamental stone walls, had been built poorly in war-time.  Nicholls teenagers would come and dare each other to get near the snakes in Snake Woods, sometimes fatally.  They left trash down there and grafitti on the buildings. Someone broke all the remaining windows which speeded decay. Letters the County wrote the Muellers went unanswered; they were hoping the County would take the land. Erosion from the ever-present wind and water set in and crept out from the desertified camp, leaving vast areas of exposed limestone.\lang1033\par

